In many countries other than the US,space is at a premium,so the dead only 
get to lease a grave,at least until a few years pass,then they are removed 
to make room for the next occupant. The remains are either cremated,or the 
bones put into a mass permanent grave called an ossuary to further break 
down. In this gentleman's case,there are also several clues to being 
autopsied. The cranial cut,the string holding the chest closed for the Y 
incision,and the black bag removed from the chest cavity is where the med 
examiner puts the removed organs back into the body. All of this minus the 
bones will prolly be incinerated with the old casket.﻿

For those who don't understand what's happening: The person had an autopsy 
before burial, they cut the skull in half to remove the brain for analysis. 
They also check other organs too then place them all in a plastic bag and 
put it in the chest cavity. 
They suture the body back together before burial. That's why you saw a 
plastic bag under the rib cage when they were taking the body apart. It 
looks like the person had died under suspicious circumstances and was being 
exhumed for further analysis. Obviously this couldn't have been done if the 
person was cremated.﻿

This is definitely not fake.  This is actually very common and in no means 
disrespectful to the dead.  The person here is buried in an "oven vault". 
 You can see the oven vaults at the end of the video.  They are a very 
common sight for anyone who has visited a New Orleans cemetery.  

What happens is the person is buried in a wooden casket in an above ground 
family vault.  The vault naturally reaches very high temperatures 
internally and basically the body is slowly cremated in a sense.  When the 
next person in the family dies, if a year has passed, the vault is cleared 
out for the next burial.  Cemetery workers place the bones into a box which 
is seen in the video.  The bones are then interred in a space below the 
burial vault.  The casket and clothing are then burnt.  This allows for a 
large number of family members to be buried together in a smaller space. 
 Check out the huge list of people buried in one crypt next time you visit 
New Orleans.﻿
